Not 100% sure what you mean, but you can grab the category scores directly from the category objects.

v2
```js
const results = await lighthouse(...)
for (const category of results.reportCategories) {
  console.log(category.id, category.score)
}
```

v3
```js
const {lhr} = await lighthouse(...)
for (const [categoryId, category] of Object.entires(lhr.categories) {
  console.log(categoryId, category.score)
}
```

The `results` and `lhr` variables above are roughly the same as if you were saving the `lighthouse --output=json` to a file and reading that.

There's not really a blessed way to do this. Our strategy for reusing logic between audits is mostly using computed artifacts. Is there a particular audit you're wanting to use that we should consider a computed artifact?

As a workaround we've used in the past, you could require in the audit class and invoke the audit yourself. DISCLAIMER: the paths/impls might be brittle and aren't guaranteed between minor version bumps.

```js
const SpeedIndexAudit = require('lighthouse/lighthouse-core/audits/speed-index.js')

class MyAudit extends Audit {
  static async audit(artifacts, context) {
    const {rawValue} = await SpeedIndexAudit.audit(artifacts, context)
    ...
  }
}
```
